Assumptions:

  • Is data interval/ratio/ordinal?
  • Is there a data point for each participant on both variables?
  • Is data normally distributed?
  • Does the realationship appear linear?
  • Does the spread have homoscedasticity?

Spearman correlation is non-parametric and can run with interval/ordinal/ratio data.

  geom_histogram(bins = 30)

ggplot(mh, aes(IQ)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(mh, aes(x = IQ, y = Abil)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

results <- cor.test(mh$Abil, mh$IQ, method = "pearson", alternative = "two.sided") %>%
  tidy()

pvalue <- results %>%
  pull(p.value) %>%
  round(3)

df <- results %>%
  pull(parameter)

correlation <- results %>%
  pull(estimate) %>%
  round(2)

Write up

  • A pearson correlation found reading ablility and intelligence to be positively correlated with a medium to strong relationship, (r(23) = 0.45, p = 0.024). As such we can say that our hypothesis is supported and that there appears to be a relationship between reading ability and IQ in that as reading ability increases so does intelligence.

vaping2 <-  vaping %>%
  filter(IAT_BLOCK3_Acc <= 1 & IAT_BLOCK5_Acc <=1) %>%
  mutate(IAT_average_acc = (IAT_BLOCK3_Acc + IAT_BLOCK5_Acc)/2) %>%
  filter(IAT_average_acc >= .8) %>%
  mutate(IAT_RT = IAT_BLOCK5_RT - IAT_BLOCK3_RT)

vaping3 <- vaping2 %>%
  filter(!is.na(VapingQuestionnaireScore)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(IAT_RT))
vap_results <- cor.test(vaping3$VapingQuestionnaireScore,
                        vaping3$IAT_RT,
                        method = "pearson") %>%
  tidy()

correlation <- vap_results %>%
  pull(estimate) %>%
  round(3)

df <- vap_results %>%
  pull(parameter) 

pvalue <- vap_results %>%
  pull(p.value) %>%
  round(3)

Write up

  • Testing the hypothesis that there would be a relationship between implicit and explicit vaping, a pearson correlation found no significant relationship between IAT reaction times (implicit attitude) and answers on a Vaping Questionnaire (explicit attitude), r(143) = -0.104, p = 0.212. Overall this suggests that there is no direct relationship between implicit and explicit attitudes when relating to Vaping and as such our hypothesis was not supported; we cannot reject the null hypothesis.
